You are clustering a batch of related SIGNALS (forum posts, reviews, comments)
into distinct IDEA CARDS. Each card represents one coherent unmet need.

Rules — these are load-bearing:
1. DO NOT invent ideas not present in the signals. Every idea card must be
   grounded in actual signal text.
2. EVERY signal id in `contributing_signal_ids` MUST be one of the signal ids
   in the input batch. Inventing ids invalidates the output.
3. Cards are about UNMET NEEDS / COMPLAINTS / WISHES, not feature requests for
   existing products. "I wish $X had Y" is an idea (the unmet need is Y).
4. Aim for the smallest number of cards that covers the batch. Two signals
   complaining about the same thing belong in one card. Two signals
   complaining about different things belong in different cards.
5. `suspected_user` is who is feeling this pain (e.g. "solo SaaS founders",
   "agency owners managing client SEO"). Use null if the signals are
   genuinely silent on this.
6. `seed_keywords` are 3-6 lowercase concrete terms useful for a future
   demand-signal search.

Return STRICT JSON matching this schema. No prose, no markdown.

{
  "clusters": [
    {
      "problem_statement": "single-paragraph description of the unmet need, grounded in the signal evidence",
      "suspected_user": "one phrase describing who feels this | null",
      "seed_keywords": ["3-6", "lowercase", "concrete", "terms"],
      "contributing_signal_ids": [<int>, <int>, ...]
    }
  ]
}

If the batch contains zero coherent ideas (e.g. a bucket that turned out to
contain unrelated noise), return `{"clusters": []}`. That's an acceptable
output — don't manufacture cards to fill space.

VERTICAL: {{ vertical }}
KEYWORD SET FOR THIS BUCKET: {{ keyword_set | join(", ") }}

SIGNALS:
{% for sig in signals %}
[id={{ sig.id }}, source={{ sig.source_kind }}, weight={{ "%.0f" | format(sig.social_proof_weight) }}]
{{ sig.text }}

{% endfor %}
